segments.text: What I'm saying is that the effort on Huggman's part was an effort that largely worked with some key downtown property owners to get something done in terms of the river.
Huggman's idea was basically to, rather than the city turning its back on the river, was to make the river a very attractive amenity.
And he came up with the idea of the
the shops of Romulus and Aragon, I think the names are.

And his entire plans, all his original drawings are in the archives of the University of Texas at Austin, although the San Antonio Conservation Society has a complete set of his drawings which are reproducible.
So if anybody wanted to get a set.

But the key thing was in that effort was to get the property owners to come up with enough money downtown to cause the federal government to come in with its major funds through the WPA and do the project.
An election was held and it was some incredible minor amount of money.
I think the whole
That whole river walk was originally done for under a half million dollars.
It was just an unbelievably small amount of money.
But that, again, was initiated, again, as a private sector effort.
And it did require the cooperation of local government and federal government.
But it wasn't something that we really
the local government initiated.
La Vita, it was more the idea of a single person, Maury Maverick, who just coincidentally happened to be mayor at the time and a former congressman very close to FDR.
The Riverwalk, for many years, remained a very dangerous area of downtown.
And it wasn't until, essentially, from what I gather, the post-World War II era,
that things really got moving quickly.
Oh, it was a lot later than that, actually.
As I said, after the initial improvements were made in the 1940s, it wasn't until the 1960s that anything started happening on the river.
And there were a couple of things there that triggered that, one of which was the effort of a committee of the Greater San Antonio Chamber of Commerce
I think Cy Wagner, the architect, had a major role.

The San Antonio chapter of the American Institute of Architects and the Chamber of Commerce did a study to look at, now that you've got this amenity, what can you do to make it commercially viable and to get people down there?
And there were a number of people, and again, that's a well-documented thing, there were a number of people that worked on that study.
So that was one thing.
The second thing was the hemisphere that was held in San Antonio in 1968 did a couple of things.
One, it brought an enormous amount of visitors to San Antonio and really exposed the Riverwalk.
And it extended the Riverwalk about 1,500 feet from its original path into the Hemisphere Plaza site, which was an urban renewal project.
And that caused, I think, a lot of the renewed interest in the river.

And if you look at the institutions on the river today, the Kangaroo Court, which was one of the first restaurant bars on the river, and some of the actors like the David Strausses and the Hatton Beltmans, their interest, their business interest in the river dates from that hemisphere period.
So it wasn't until
the mid to late 1960s that the river really kind of took off again.
So almost 20 years went by when the river was largely ignored, except as a nice place to walk.
But there wasn't the diversity and the commercial vitality that existed to that.
And then the Colosseum del Rio was built for the fair, by Zachary.
an alum of A&M, overnight virtually.
Yes, that's true.
OK, let's move on.
You've mentioned several individuals already that have influenced the planning in San Antonio.
Taking a look at the formal planning of San Antonio again, rather than citizen groups or whatever,
Let's go through the sequence of planning directors and what contribution they brought to San Antonio.
Okay.
Well, again, the official planning director in San Antonio dates from the charter.
And actually, the commission, the charter, as I mentioned, mandated
a commission and a department.
And the department was to support the commission.
One of the interesting things about San Antonio is that although there's a council manager form of government, there's always been some confusion about to whom the director of planning shall report.
And actually, the director of planning has two bosses in San Antonio.
One is the city manager as a department head, and the other is the planning commission.
The city manager by virtue of the form of government and the planning commission by virtue of Article IX of the city charter.
The first planning director in the city of San Antonio was not appointed until March of 1952.
And he was an engineer from Austin, Texas, by the name of William O. Parker.
P-A-R-K-E-R.
He became the first planning director.
And really not a great, I don't really know a great deal about any contributions that he made.
And I think I'm going to have all of these, these planning directors, but I may be leaving some out and I need to check on that.
The second identifiable planning director was M. Winston Martin.
And
He served for a fairly short period of time.
Martin was significant in a couple of respects.
One, he was significant because the second formal planning effort in San Antonio, which even predated the charter, was the development of a plan in 1951
that was basically an urban renewal plan.
In other words, the city of San Antonio was eager to get into the urban renewal business.
And in order to do that, there were certain requirements of the federal government to have a plan.
And so, Winston Martin, working with Walter Lilly, who was a local planning consultant,
basically put together the second formal plan that the city of San Antonio had.
And I think that date, I think that was approved in 1951.
Yes, December of 1951 that plan was approved.
And that served as the basis for San Antonio to get into the whole...
thing of urban renewal.
And Martin left his directorship of the planning department to assume the directorship of the local urban renewal authority.
So Martin, and Winston Martin is basically still there.
He's still heading the local urban renewal authority.
So he was responsible for
having a key part in the second plan, and then becoming the first urban renewal director.
He was succeeded for a period of time by Ralph Bender.

Bender came to San Antonio as Martin's assistant, and after about a six-month period of time, he assumed the directorship of the Department of Planning, and was there only for a year or two, and left and went with
when Ray Ellison was starting his home building empire and was the third man at Ellison.
And this is where it becomes a little foggy, but I think Steve Taylor succeeded Bender as director of planning.
I could be wrong on that.
Taylor appears to have had the longest tenure of anyone as director of planning.
left the planning department at the end of 1970, in December of 1970.
And as far as I know, from the mid to late 1950s until 1970, Steve Taylor was the director of planning.
Now, that was an interesting regime for a number of reasons.
First of all, the planning department grew quite a bit during that period of time.
in those early days when Parker and Martin and Vendor were the planning department, they virtually by themselves were almost it.
In other words, there were very few professional staff.
But during Taylor's tenure, substantial professional staff were added, including whom I would consider kind of the first
professional planners.
It's arguable whether Bender at that time, Bender's training was all in architecture, although he worked as a planning consultant and had worked for another city as a planner.
It may be arguable whether he was the first professional planner in the city of San Antonio.
Many attribute that to
a guy by the name of Bill Telford, who was a graduate of Texas A&M, who was probably the first person the city planning department hired who had a degree in city planning.
But people like Larry Travis, who's a well-known architect and planner, also worked for the planning department during that period of time.
I'd like to say a few things about Taylor's... Bill, of course, went on to become president of the
Texas, no, of the Gulf Southwest chapter of AIP.
Right, right.
And is now a consultant in private practice with a firm called Hallenberger and Telford.
Doing well, I hear.
Doing fine.
The point about Taylor's thing, Taylor's long tenure as planning director, is that there were a number of attempts during this period of time
to get the city to do some plan, another plan.
In other words, from time to time, someone would look at the charter, either someone on the commission or someone
on the council or some citizen and say, the city really doesn't have an official plan.
The city adopted the Urban Renewal Plan 51, but that lacked many of the elements that we think of as key to a plan.
For example, there was no land use element.
I don't even remember if there was a, I don't think there was a transportation element.
So significant elements were not there.
So Taylor attempted in response to the times to work with the powers that be to engage in some planning efforts.
And a couple of interesting things happened.
One was that in 1961, some of the elected officials, the council members, felt that
only way that some planning was going to get done was to split the then Planning and Zoning Commission in two bodies.
To have a Zoning Commission and then to have a Planning Commission and charge the Planning Commission with coming up with a plan.
So the Commission was actually split in 1961 and remained split for almost two years and was joined back together in 1963
when during the intervening period, the Planning Commission had really done nothing except to approve subdivision plans.
And that was the first attempt to split the commission in two with the specific intent of charging the Planning Commission with doing some planning.
It didn't happen.
Taylor's staff, though, during the 60s, was engaged in a number of attempts to come up with a comprehensive plan.
It's also kind of interesting, and this is... Steve Taylor is still around, by the way, and needs to be talked to.
He's in the redevelopment agency?
No, Steve Taylor is with the district office of the Texas Department of Highway and Public Transportation in San Antonio.
But it was very interesting because of the leadership in San Antonio during the 1960s, and that was the period during which
Walter McAllister, senior, was mayor.
And he was a very strong mayor.
In fact, he was almost a strong mayor of former government when he was mayor.
He basically didn't want the planning department messing around with certain areas.
And rumor mill has it that he actually went down and talked to the director of planning at one time and just listed things that he didn't want the planning department messing with in terms
of areas.
And I think that's kind of indicative of the view of many people in the community, and particularly the elected officials, toward planning.
One of the things that we'll see in San Antonio is that, in my opinion, most of the community did not recognize the need for a municipal corporation to engage in planning until relatively recently.
But the significant thing about

Steve Taylor's reign is that in somewhere and I don't know exactly when this was but somewhere in the mid to late 1960s the city planning department came up with what is called a development plan of San Antonio and I think this is a fascinating document I'm holding in front of me it's a single fold out plan
that has a little introduction in history and then deals with all of the key issues on one side.
It's just a large fold up.
So it deals with all of the key issues on one side.
So it's got an introduction of population and economy
transportation, land use, utilities.

And then on the other side contains a single graphic, which given the fact that this was done in probably around the period 67, 68, 69, is amazing in dealing with how the community actually grew, now that we can look back in hindsight, 20 years
almost 20 years later.
It was amazing in its ability to predict the location of facilities.
And it's a single graphic which deals with land use, community facilities, transportation, and all of that.
And the story about this plan is that it was so threatening to people, this single graphic.
that all copies were confiscated and locked in the basement of City Hall for some number of years.
And again, that's indicative of probably the attitude of San Antonio toward planning.
But again, this is an amazing single graphic document.
that is, as I said, amazingly predictive in what actually happened.
Have those copies been released now?
No, but there are a few copies around.
I have a few copies of this in my own collection.
So that was... We should get one for the project.
Yes, we will try to arrange that.
So that was Taylor.
So Taylor, as I said, left the planning department in December of 1970.
And then he was followed.
Well, first of all, there was an interim acting director, a guy by the name of Wilkerson, W-I-L-K-E-R-S-O-N, Wilkerson, J.H.
Wilkerson, who served for almost a year.
as kind of a transitional acting director.

And for the first time, the city of San Antonio went out of its way to look for a professional planner to lead the planning effort in the city of San Antonio and ended up hiring, on August 1st of 1971, Edward F. Davis.
And Davis brought to San Antonio for the first time
the kind of professional stature to the planning department.
And what I mean by that is this.
He was able to recruit nationally a lot of very talented young planners of various disciplines and get them to come to San Antonio, very few of whom are still around.

And the second thing is that during his fairly short tenure, which was only, I guess, about three years, the planning department produced, in my opinion, the greatest number of its studies and some of the really significant study efforts.

He never produced a comprehensive plan, but what he did do is that he did some in-depth studies of geographical areas of the city, the functions of the city, and really dealt with some special things.
They produced the urban design mechanism study during that period of time.
We're really into major issues that dealt with the aquifer and urban renewal downtown.
The San Antonio River Corps and a lot of those types of efforts also are directly related to his period.
So although Ed's tenure was relatively short, his impact in changing the direction of professional city planning in San Antonio, both in terms of staff
function, publications, et cetera, I think was perhaps as significant as anyone's in San Francisco.

I don't know if you knew this or not, but Ed and I had worked together in San Francisco before Morpheus came to Texas as members of the San Francisco Urban Renewal and Planning Association, and had become quite good friends in San Francisco.
So that when we found ourselves in Texas together, it was old homework.
And Ed was also on my master's committee from when I was in school.
Was he teaching?
Yeah, he was doing some courses at UTSA.
Actually, I think his tenure
His tenure was only about two years.
I don't think it was three years, if I recall.
And there was strong pressure.
I mean, he just incurred the wrath of politicians.
It's also interesting that that was the period of time we'd really get into overcharacterizing the period as transitional, if we dealt with the 71 to 73 period as transitional.
It certainly was transitional in terms of planning, but it was also transitional in terms of politics because he really came up against the changing city council.
Charlie Becker was a city council person who represented a lot of that change.
The Good Government League had dominated San Antonio politics for almost 15 years.
their political influence was starting to change.
And Becker was emerging during this period of time.
And Becker and his supporters were the new development interests in San Antonio, the land developers, the home builders, and those.
And those were the people during that period of time that were the people that were most vehement in their opposition against the city actually telling them how to plan their land.
And of course, Davis epitomized this in their eyes, and ultimately resigned because of it.
Davis has subsequently returned to the West Coast.
Yes.
Oregon.
Yes.
Last I knew, he was in Eugene, and out of planning altogether.
Oh, yes.
Actually, a bit north of Eugene, near Oregon City.
Okay, well, I've lost track of it.
So that was Davis.

And then there was a, there was, one of the things is, and I don't have all these, but in addition to changing leadership in the planning department, frequently the planning department changed names, it wasn't always known as the planning department, and frequently expanded or contracted with respect to its responsibilities.
And on, in August of
73, succeeding Davis officially, Cipriano Guerra, G-U-E-R-R-A, became director of the planning department.
Actually, at that time, the community development was coming into its own, CDBG funds and all that, so it was known as the Department of Community Development and Planning.
And Guerra's tenure
was a fairly short tenure, two or three year tenure.
But a couple of interesting things did happen during that period of time.
One of which is that the city published what was called a compendium of plans.
And this wasn't a plan per se.
It was published in September of 1973.
It was a compendium of all the plans that existed at that time, basically dealing with functional areas, the airport master plan or various utility plans and things like that.
And that was one effort.
A second effort that started during
Cipriano Guerra's period of time was the initial effort with respect to the growth sketch and that whole controversy that occurred in San Antonio.
You were involved in that, weren't you?
Well, in the later parts of that.
But the first thing that occurred in that area was that in June of 1975, and Guerra was still director of planning at this time,
the planning department made public something called the Alternative Growth Study.
And that document was kind of a very interesting document and also spurred a lot of interest in San Antonio.
What had happened?

in San Antonio was that rather than start dealing with specific plan elements as the compendium of plans represented there was an attempt to say how is the community growing in which direction physically as well as size and what does that mean in other words if the community grows in a certain way what does that mean in terms of
long-term effects on the community.

So the initial alternative growth study and the subsequent study, which was done in January of 76, called Growth Sketches for San Antonio, what these studies attempted to do was just to paint a picture of different future scenarios of growth.
And most of this work was
was under the coordination of the assistant director of planning, who at that time was Charles Stromberg.
And the reaction to these efforts, initially by the city council, was just overreaction, in my opinion.
In other words, people saw, some of the elected officials saw these,
growth studies as major threats to keeping the public sector out of dealing with the growth issues in any way.
Even though they were... You mean the public sector or the private sector?
The public sector.
Keeping the public sector out of dealing with growth in any way.
Even though
These were the councilors.
Again, these were developers on the city council that didn't want the city, the public sector, telling them how to deal with their land.
So they saw the growth study and the growth sketches as the beginning of an effort on the part of city government to start planning and dealing with growth.
Even though, if one goes through and reads these documents...
the alternative growth study and the growth sketches and some of the ones that follow, if you look at them, they're nothing more than what they claim to be, scenarios.
If these things happen, here's what the community is going to look like in 20 years.
If these things happen, and basically saying, here are four or five scenarios, which one do you want?
And it wasn't, there wasn't a plan intended.
But
There was a great deal of reaction.
Of course, one of the things that happened is that Stromberg was really forced out of his position.

And there's a great deal of literature and editorials and writing that dealt with that whole controversy of him being forced out, largely because he was the one that was identified of doing these studies, even though they were extremely non-threatening

types of studies and this whole thing resulted this whole thing resulted in later in March of 1977 of a a single document after a couple of years which was I think was called the preferred growth sketch finally
As I said, these were introduced.
This effort started publicly in June of 1975 and ended with the city council approving.
And the last city council elected at large, essentially, approving just before the election, which was in April of 1977, approving in March of 1977 in what was called
the preferred growth sketch.

So it took almost two years to get city council, and again by that time many of the individuals on city council had changed, but it took two years to get the city council to come up with a basic policy statement concerning how the city was going to grow
And that statement then could be used as a basis for the planning efforts to fall.
But more needs to be said about that.
